SIMPLE: thunderbolt
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thunderbolt
<hw>Thun"der*bolt`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
shaft of lightning; a brilliant stream of electricity passing from one
part of the heavens to another, or from the clouds to the
earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something resembling lightning in suddenness and
effectiveness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Scipios' worth, those <qex>thunderbolts</qex> of war.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Vehement threatening or censure; especially,
ecclesiastical denunciation; fulmination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He severely threatens such with the <qex>thunderbolt</qex> of
excommunication.</q> <rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <def>A belemnite, or
thunderstone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thunderbolt beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
long-horned beetle (<spn>Arhopalus fulminans</spn>) whose larva bores in
the trunk of oak and chestnut trees. It is brownish and bluish-black,
with W-shaped whitish or silvery markings on the elytra.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thunderburst</ent>⟦br⟧
